I chose the Area Graph option in RAWGraphs, which allowed me to place the years along the x-axis and group the data by 
country along the y-axis. The values are then represented by the width of the bar, which changes horizontally to reflect the
change over time. The width corresponds to the debt each year (as % of GDP).

Of the options built into RAWGraphs, this seemed like the best option in terms of 
presenting this many data points all at once and showing the change over time in a (somewhat) readable way.
I still find it somewhat overwhelming to look at, but it made more sense than the other formats I tried (bump chart,
horizon graph, stream graph). For example,
the bump chart seems to be better to use for percentages of a constant whole (i.e., maybe if we were looking at 
percentage of components of GDP for one specific country over time, where the components 
would be different percentages that always added up to a 100% total). For this data, the bump chart had a terrible
"spaghetti" effect. The horizon graph and stream graph were essentially completely unreadable for me with this type of dataset.

However, this format still has significant disadvantages. For one thing, I didn't find a way to add indicators of what
the absolute percentages were for the countries: the bars let you roughly tell that one country's percentage
was bigger than another for a given year, or that a country's percentage grew from year 1 to year 2, but there's no real
indicator of whether the percentage grew from 40% to 50% or from 50% to 80%.

The countries could also be represented in different colors, but I chose to minimize the number of colors (instead
of using the rainbowy color scheme that RAWGraphs initially used by default).
I used ColorBrewer for inspiration (and colorblind-friendliness). I selected one of its colorblind-friendly 3-color
diverging schemes, but I ended up only using the two end colors, and then I replaced the original middle color (yellow)
with a gray that was less overwhelming and easier to see against a white background.

I also didn't have as much control as I would have liked over the grouping and presentation of the data in RAWGraphs. 
For one thing, I had to choose one of its presets for sorting the countries, and it was not entirely transparent about
how it was performing the ascending or descending sorting with this dataset. For example, since there were multiple data points
for each country (generally one for each year, but with some missing data), I might have wanted to sort based on the 2017 data point,
or the 1999 data point, or the most recent data point available for that country,
depending on what my audience needed to see. RAWGraphs didn't let me do that.

I'll try this with Tableau and/or ggplot later to see if I can add a 4th visualization that I'm happier with.
